  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. Here are some of the most important:\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988) (Vienna Convention):** This convention, while primarily focused on drug trafficking, was the first major international agreement to recognize money laundering as a criminal offense. It requires states to criminalize the laundering of drug-related proceeds and to cooperate in international investigations and prosecutions.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000) (Palermo Convention):** This convention builds on the Vienna Convention by extending the scope of money laundering offenses to cover the proceeds of a wider range of serious crimes, including human trafficking, arms smuggling, and corruption. It also promotes international cooperation in preventing and combating organized crime, including money laundering.\n\n*   **International Convention for the Suppression of the Financing of Terrorism (1999):** This convention requires states to criminalize the financing of terrorism and to take measures to prevent and suppress such financing. It also addresses money laundering related to terrorist activities.\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF):** While not a treaty, the FATF is an intergovernmental body that sets international standards and promotes the effective implementation of legal, regulatory, and operational measures for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system. The FATF's 40 Recommendations on Money Laundering and 9 Special Recommendations on Terrorist Financing are considered the global standard in this area.  Many countries have implemented these recommendations into their own national laws and regulations.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990) and revised version (2005):** These conventions aim to facilitate international cooperation in the investigation, prosecution, and confiscation of proceeds from crime, including money laundering.\n\nIn addition to these international agreements, many countries have their own national laws and regulations to combat money laundering, which are often based on the international standards set by the FATF and other organizations.\n\n**Key aspects addressed by these laws and conventions:**\n\n*   **Criminalization:** Requiring countries to criminalize money laundering as a distinct offense.\n*   **Prevention:** Implementing measures to prevent money laundering, such as customer due diligence requirements for financial institutions.\n*   **International Cooperation:** Encouraging countries to cooperate in investigating and prosecuting money laundering cases, including sharing information and providing mutual legal assistance.\n*   **Confiscation:** Enabling the seizure and confiscation of the proceeds of crime, including money laundered funds.\n\nIt is important to note that the effectiveness of these international laws and conventions depends on their implementation and enforcement by individual countries.",
